\begin_layout Abstract
We present a mathematical framework based on quantum interval-valued probability
 measures to study the effect of experimental imperfections and finite precision
 measurements on defining aspects of quantum mechanics such as contextuality
 and the Born rule.
 While foundational results such as the Kochen-Specker and Gleason theorems
 fail to hold in general in a world with limited resources, when we allow
 infinite precision, their validity is recovered.
 
